The value of a silver coin under Texas's new law is determined by its market price at the time of the transaction, as set by the Texas Comptroller. This price fluctuates daily based on global market rates for silver. This ensures merchants receive dollars, not physical silver. The system aims to be practical but depends on rules still being finalized, effective May 2027. Price volatility and merchant acceptance remain concerns.

It's a shame they stole everything from Microsoft. 😉

Windows Mobile was launched in 2000. Email, calendar, tasks, notes, media player, even versions of Excel, Word, and PPT. 

Microsoft also produced the first wearable internet capable computer or Smart Personal Object Technology, aka SPOT watch. You could read text messages and do things like follow stocks. That was 2004. Still before the release of the iPhone. 

Windows Phone 7 was released in 2010. It was the first to have Live Tiles, Widgets, and other features that Apple released later on iPhones. 

Then there was the Microsoft Band released in 2014. A wearable that monitored health, steps, stairs, messaging, phone calls, etc. 

Apple made an announcement about an Apple Watch when they found out about the Microsoft Band, but it wasn't actually produced until 2015. 

Then there's Surface with a built-in kickstand, detachable keyboard, and ink integration released in 2012. Apple added features that were similar later to its iPad. 

Microsoft actually created superior products. Apple just had better marketing. (Speaking from experience on this. I still have all of these Microsoft devices. Even a SPOT watch. 😉)

If you made it this far. Thank you for coming to my Eliza Talk on Microsoft device history. 🤣😂

DTC shoppers report spending less in 2025 than any year we've tracked.

Here's why that matters.

In 2023 we launched a survey experience at @KnoCommerce that lets brands opt in to asking a set of questions that are benchmarked and aggregated across our entire ecosystem.

Among those questions are economic sentiment questions that we use to power https://t.co/Z5lHNZz7As alongside @TaylorHoliday, @RSteveData, and the CTC team.

Two of those questions tell you everything you need to know about the state of the consumer.

#1 (blue) - We're asking if they're currently spending more or less than typical online.

#2 (red) - We're asking if they plan to spend more or less in the future online.

As you can see, both numbers are the lowest we've tracked since we launched this over 2 years ago.

Now here's where this gets really interesting...

We're specifically asking about online buying habits.

Why does this matter?

These numbers might not match what we're seeing in the broader economy.

For example, my family is 5 people.

Those 5 people need to eat.

That will be no different 3 months from now than it is today.

So I'm going to prioritize groceries, gas, childcare, etc.

If I'm strapped for cash, my overall spending may not dip much, but my online spending might drop in half.

Why? Most eCommerce/DTC spending is discretionary.

It's coming from your "extra" budget, not your "I need to feed my family" budget.

Again, that's most, not all.

Amazon spending also likely looks much different than Shopify spending.

I'm more likely to go there for basics, while hitting up Shopify stores for my non-essentials.

So I'll be honest, I'm not 100% convinced the charts here from @rishabhmjain are conclusive.

But for what it's worth, consumers tend to agree.

And they are the ones paying all of our bills, after all.

3. Did Sci-Hub’s new token impact $SciHub holders?

Yes, significantly. Most $SciHub holders bought the token because its contract address (CA) was listed on the official Sci-Hub website. Without that, $SciHub likely would’ve gone to zero like many failed celebrity or company-themed donation tokens.

Imagine if Tesla replaced its stock ticker on its official site without handling the old stock — shareholders would be outraged. This would never be allowed in any regulated securities market.
Although Alex may never have considered $SciHub as Sci-Hub’s stock or official token, to investors, public information pointed in that direction. No one could read Alex’s mind — and no one could have foreseen this sudden reversal.

At the time the new token launched, over 15,000 addresses held $SciHub, and the token was listed on many exchanges. The true number of holders exceeded many Web3 tokens and would rival major companies in the traditional stock market.

There was no prior announcement, no community coordination. Many holders likely didn’t even know it happened. They couldn’t react in time, and now face steep losses.
Alex told users to sell or swap $scihub to the new token — but the majority never even saw that message. Prices plunged due to the token announcement, and unlike before, this time there’s no recovery hope — just real losses.
